    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="bibliography" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                    <p>
                        <bibl><ptr target="IDodoneDVC"/> <citedRange>168B</citedRange>. </bibl>
                        </p>
                    <p>
                      Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#AnagnostopoulouGalaniMenti2022"/>, <citedRange>243 n. 16</citedRange> (on questions regarding professional activities, simple mention)</bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#Giannakis2024a"/>, <citedRange>41</citedRange> (on dialect).</bibl></p>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/>περὶ χώρας 
                    <lb n="2"/>καὶ ἐκκαρπι
                    <lb n="3" break="no"/>ῶν
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
                <app loc="ll. 2-3">
                    <rdg resp="#IDodoneDVC">ε<supplied reason="omitted">ὐ</supplied>καρπιῶν <note>Méndez Dosuna <foreign xml:lang="la">apud</foreign></note></rdg>
                </app>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                <p>About land and its produce.</p>
            </div>
                <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="es">
                    <p>Sobre la tierra y los frutos.</p>
                </div>
                
            <div type="commentary" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                <p>The feminine noun <foreign xml:lang="grc">ἐκκαρπία</foreign> is now attested in the dossier of documents concerning the sale of land from Larissa, dated to 219 BC (<bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>63.406, l.17</citedRange></bibl>). According to the first editors (<bibl><ptr target="#HellyTziafalias2013"/>, <citedRange>151-152 n. 13</citedRange></bibl>), it is a hapax meaning <foreign xml:lang="fr">“les productions (littéralement les fruits qui viennent de)”.</foreign> </p>
                
            <p n="Ithaca Results">Ithaca predicts Phrygia (64.95%) and Bithynia (19.99%) as the most probable geographical origins of the inscription, whereas Epirus ranks only ninth, with a mere 0.53% probability. As for its chronological attribution, the highest probability falls at the beginning of the third century AD, specifically AD 210–220. See <ref target="https://dodonaonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/IDodoneOnline168B_2026_06_25.html">Ithaca results</ref> and <ref target="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/IDodone/IDodoneOnline/refs/heads/main/ithaca-results/IDodoneOnline168B.md">metadata</ref>, and a snapshot of the <ref target="https://dodonaonline.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/IDodoneOnline168B_geographical-attribution_2026_06.jpg">geographical attribution</ref>.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
